Distributed Exposure Convergence (DEC v1.0)

Status: Canonical Pattern
Domain: Cross-domain (biology, social systems, information networks)
Ethics Gate: ≥ 0.7 (value-neutral mechanism; outcomes depend on use)

⸻

1. Core Definition

Distributed Exposure Convergence (DEC) is the process by which a group’s internal state converges over time through repeated, network-mediated exchanges of environmental inputs and interactions.

⸻

2. One-Line Compression

“Local sampling + network exchange → global convergence.”

⸻

3. Mechanism (Minimal Model)

Let:
	•	Aᵢ(t) = state of individual i at time t
	•	E(t) = shared environment (dynamic reservoir)
	•	N(i) = neighbors/interactions of i
	•	S() = sampling function (what gets picked up)
	•	U() = update function (how state changes)

⸻

Update Rule

Aᵢ(t+1) = U( Aᵢ(t), S(E(t)), S(Aⱼ(t)) for j ∈ N(i) )

⸻

Interpretation

Each individual:
	1.	Samples environment
	2.	Samples others
	3.	Updates internal state
	4.	Feeds back into environment/network

⸻

4. System Properties

4.1 Semi-Random Constraint Field
	•	Micro-level = stochastic
	•	Macro-level = structured
	•	Governed by constraints (environment, topology, behavior)

⸻

4.2 Network Topology Sensitivity
	•	Dense networks → fast convergence
	•	Sparse networks → fragmentation
	•	Hubs → disproportionate influence

⸻

4.3 Gradient Coupling
	•	Exchanges follow existing gradients
	•	Convergence accelerates around attractors

⸻

4.4 Bidirectional Shaping
	•	Individuals shape group
	•	Group reshapes individuals
	•	Continuous feedback loop

⸻

4.5 Value Neutrality

DEC amplifies:
	•	beneficial traits
	•	harmful traits
	•	neutral drift

No inherent directionality.

⸻

5. Domains of Instantiation

Biological
	•	Microbiome convergence in households
	•	Immune exposure patterns

Social
	•	Norms, slang, behavior
	•	Emotional tone / group mood

Informational
	•	Memes, ideas, narratives
	•	Belief alignment

Digital Systems
	•	Recommendation loops
	•	Algorithmic clustering

⸻

6. Failure Modes

6.1 Pathological Convergence
	•	Disease spread
	•	Toxic norm reinforcement
	•	Echo chambers

⸻

6.2 Gradient Collapse
	•	Loss of diversity
	•	Overfitting to dominant signal

⸻

6.3 Hub Corruption
	•	Central node injects harmful pattern
	•	Rapid network-wide propagation

⸻

6.4 False Attractor Formation
	•	Convergence around low-quality signal
	•	Misalignment with reality

⸻

7. Control Levers (Abstract, non-operational)

(Framed at a systems level—no tactical misuse guidance)
	•	Topology: who connects to who
	•	Exposure Frequency: interaction rate
	•	Signal Weighting: what gets reinforced
	•	Environmental Shaping: what’s available to sample
	•	Diversity Preservation: prevent collapse

⸻

8. Relation to Other Pantheon Constructs
	•	Gradient Attraction Principle (GAP): defines direction of flow
	•	DEC: defines network-mediated distribution

⸻

Integration:

GAP sets the slopes
DEC moves the mass across the terrain

⸻

9. Invariants
	1.	No convergence without exchange
	2.	No exchange without adjacency
	3.	No stability without constraint
	4.	No guarantee of positive outcome

⸻

10. Clean Boundary Statement

DEC explains how states spread and align,
not whether they should.

⸻

11. Canonical Example (Neutral)
	•	A group shares space daily
	•	Each member samples environment + each other
	•	Over time:
	•	microbiomes shift
	•	language aligns
	•	behaviors synchronize

No central control required.

